Constructor Injection is the most common way to implement Dependency Injection in .NET. Dependencies are declared as parameters in a class constructor, and the .NET runtime automatically provides the concrete implementations when creating the class instance.

**Example:**
```csharp
public class OrderService {
    private readonly IOrderRepository _repository;
    public OrderService(IOrderRepository repository) {
        _repository = repository;
    }
}
```

The Decorator Pattern dynamically adds behaviour to an object without modifying its class. In .NET, you wrap an existing implementation in another class implementing the same interface:

```csharp
public class LoggingRepository : IOrderRepository {
    private readonly IOrderRepository _inner;
    // Delegate to _inner, then log
}
```

You handle exceptions in async methods using standard `try/catch` blocks. If an exception occurs inside an awaited task, it is captured and re-thrown when you await the task, allowing you to catch it normally:

```csharp
try {
    await FetchDataAsync();
} catch (Exception ex) {
    _logger.LogError(ex, "Error fetching data");
}
```

`SemaphoreSlim` limits the number of concurrent threads/tasks accessing a resource. Unlike `lock`, it is async-compatible and supports `await`:

```csharp
var semaphore = new SemaphoreSlim(3); // allow 3 concurrent
await semaphore.WaitAsync();
try { /* critical work */ } finally { semaphore.Release(); }
```

Use `Interlocked.Increment` for atomic increment without a lock:

```csharp
private int _counter = 0;
Interlocked.Increment(ref _counter);
```
This is more efficient than `lock` for single-operation increments since it uses CPU-level atomic instructions.

Always use parameterized queries in Dapper by passing parameters as an anonymous object — never interpolate user input into the SQL string:

```csharp
// SAFE:
var user = await conn.QueryFirstAsync<User>("SELECT * FROM Users WHERE Id = @Id", new { Id = userId });
// DANGEROUS: "SELECT * FROM Users WHERE Id = " + userId
```

Define a navigation property collection on the 'one' side and a foreign key + navigation property on the 'many' side:

```csharp
public class Order {
    public List<OrderItem> Items { get; set; }
}
public class OrderItem {
    public int OrderId { get; set; }
    public Order Order { get; set; }
}
```
EF Core auto-detects and maps this relationship.

Auto-implemented properties allow declaring a property without writing a backing field. The compiler automatically creates a private, anonymous field behind the scenes:

```csharp
public class Product {
    public int Id { get; set; }
}
```

Records are immutable reference types with value-based equality and automatic `ToString`, `Equals`, and `GetHashCode` implementations. They also support `with` expressions to create modified copies:

```csharp
public record Person(string Name, int Age);
var updated = person with { Age = 31 };
```

Pattern matching checks a value against a shape and extracts data from it. C# supports type patterns, property patterns, and switch expressions:

```csharp
string Describe(object obj) => obj switch {
    int n when n > 0 => "Positive int",
    string s => $"String: {s}",
    null => "null",
    _ => "Unknown"
};
```

Primary constructors allow declaring constructor parameters directly on the class declaration, automatically making them available as fields throughout the class body:

```csharp
public class OrderService(IOrderRepository repo) {
    public async Task<Order> GetAsync(int id) => await repo.GetByIdAsync(id);
}
```

The `init` accessor allows a property to be set only during object initialization (including object initializers), but not after. This gives you immutable properties that can still be set at construction time:

```csharp
public class Invoice {
    public decimal Amount { get; init; }
}
```

A lambda expression is an anonymous function using `=>` syntax. It is commonly used with LINQ and delegates:

```csharp
var evens = numbers.Where(n => n % 2 == 0);
Func<int, int> square = x => x * x;
```

Extension methods allow adding new methods to existing types without modifying or subclassing them. They are defined as static methods in a static class, with the first parameter prefixed with `this`:

```csharp
public static string ToTitleCase(this string s) => ...
// Usage:
"hello world".ToTitleCase();
```

`global using` applies a `using` directive to all files in the project, eliminating repetitive `using` statements at the top of every file:

```csharp
// In GlobalUsings.cs
global using System.Text.Json;
global using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;
```
